BUG 2 — Item name dropdown: hidden below (z-index / overflow clipping)
==============================================================================
ROOT CAUSE: The item name dropdown inside the table rows is clipped by the 
table's overflow. Tables clip overflow by default — absolute children inside 
<td> get cut off at the table boundary.

FIX STEPS:

A. Find the <table> element wrapping the items rows. Add:
   style={{ borderCollapse: 'separate', borderSpacing: 0, overflow: 'visible' }}
   Also ensure the parent <div> wrapping the table does NOT have overflow-hidden 
   or overflow-auto. Change any overflow-auto to overflow-visible on the 
   table container div.

B. Find each <td> that contains an autocomplete input. Add:
   style={{ overflow: 'visible', position: 'relative' }}

C. The dropdown <ul> inside table cells: change z-index from z-50 to z-[300] 
   and use the same theme-aware classes as Bug 1 fix:
   
   <ul className="absolute z-[300] top-full left-0 mt-1 w-64 min-w-full
     bg-white dark:bg-slate-800
     border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-700
     rounded-xl shadow-xl shadow-black/10 dark:shadow-black/40
     max-h-48 overflow-auto
     ring-1 ring-black/5 dark:ring-white/5">
     
     {suggestions.map(s => (
       <li key={s.value}
         onMouseDown={() => handleTableSuggestionSelect(...)}
         className="px-3 py-2 cursor-pointer transition-colors duration-100
           text-[13px] text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-200
           hover:bg-blue-50 dark:hover:bg-blue-500/10
           hover:text-blue-700 dark:hover:text-blue-300
           first:rounded-t-xl last:rounded-b-xl">
         <div className="font-semibold">{s.label}</div>
         {s.description && (
           <div className="text-[11px] text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400">
             {s.description}
           </div>
         )}
       </li>
     ))}
   </ul>

D. If the table container has max-h + overflow-auto for scrolling, 
   you CANNOT use absolute positioning inside it reliably. In that case,
   use position: fixed for the dropdown instead of position: absolute,
   and calculate its position using getBoundingClientRect() in an 
   onFocus handler. Implement like this:
   
   - Add state: const [dropdownPos, setDropdownPos] = useState(null)
   - On input focus inside table cell:
     const rect = inputRef.current.getBoundingClientRect();
     setDropdownPos({ top: rect.bottom + window.scrollY, left: rect.left + window.scrollX, width: rect.width });
   - Render the dropdown as: style={{ position: 'fixed', top: dropdownPos.top, left: dropdownPos.left, width: Math.max(dropdownPos.width, 256), zIndex: 9999 }}
   - This escapes ALL overflow clipping entirely.

   Choose option D only if the table has overflow-auto. Otherwise option B+C is sufficient.

